  "prompt": "What is the song meaning of Hotel California?",
  "response": "\"Hotel California\" is a song by the Eagles, released in 1976. The track is known for its rich and enigmatic lyrics which have been interpreted in various ways by listeners and critics alike. The meaning is often considered to be complex and multi-layered.\n\nOne common interpretation is that \"Hotel California\" is a metaphor for the excesses of American life, particularly in the context of the 1970s Southern California lifestyle, which was marked by hedonism and decadence. The song's lyrics describe a traveler who checks into a luxurious hotel that seems inviting at first but gradually reveals a darker side. This can be seen as a metaphor for the seductive allure of fame, wealth, and pleasure, which comes with its own set of traps and consequences.\n\nThe line \"You can check out any time you like, but you can never leave\" suggests that once you fall into certain lifestyles or behaviors, it can be incredibly difficult to escape them. The song touches on themes of disillusionment, entrapment, and the idea that things are not always what they seem.\n\nUltimately, Don Henley, the Eagles' lead vocalist and one of the primary songwriters, has indicated that the song is about \"a journey from innocence to experience.\" It paints a picture of the clash between superficial glamour and the underlying darkness that can accompany it.\n\nHowever, part of the song's enduring appeal is its ambiguity, allowing listeners to draw their own conclusions and meanings from its haunting and evocative imagery.",
